    history: "Zagreb began as two rival medieval settlements — Kaptol (the bishop's seat) and Gradec (the free royal town) — separated by the Medveščak stream and joined only in 1850. The city's golden age came under the Habsburgs and especially during the 19th-century Croatian National Revival, when figures like Ljudevit Gaj and Ivan Mažuranić shaped a modern Croatian identity here. After 1991, Zagreb became the capital of independent Croatia, and today it is the country's political, economic, cultural, and academic centre.",
    facts: ["Zagreb's St Mark's Church (Crkva svetog Marka) has a tiled roof showing the coats of arms of Croatia, Dalmatia, Slavonia, and Zagreb — one of the most photographed roofs in Europe","The Mirogoj Cemetery's arcaded walls (1879, designed by Hermann Bollé) are considered one of the most beautiful cemeteries in Europe","Zagreb's Funicular (1890) is one of the shortest public transport systems in the world — 66 metres long, a 64-second ride","The Museum of Broken Relationships in Gornji Grad is a globally unique concept — donated artefacts from failed love affairs — and has won the European Museum of the Year award","The Dolac open-air market above Ban Jelačić Square has operated daily since 1930 and is the heart of the city's food culture"],
