    intro: "Zadar is northern Dalmatia's largest city — a 3,000-year-old port whose old town sits on a small peninsula jutting into the Adriatic, ringed by stone walls and Roman pavement. Famous for the Sea Organ that plays music with the waves and the Sun Salutation light installation, Zadar combines deep antiquity with bold contemporary art.",
    history: "Founded by the Liburnians and Romanised as Iadera in the 1st century BC, Zadar was for centuries the capital of Venetian Dalmatia. Its 9th-century Church of Saint Donatus, built of Roman spolia, is one of the most striking pre-Romanesque buildings in Europe. Italian-Croatian tensions defined the 20th century — Zadar was Italian between the wars, devastated by Allied bombing in 1943–44, and underwent an Italian exodus after WWII. The 1991 Homeland War damaged it again. Since 2005, Nikola Bašić's Sea Organ and Sun Salutation have transformed the city's public face.",
    facts: ["Nikola Bašić's Sea Organ (2005) turns wave motion into haunting musical chords through 35 underwater pipes — Alfred Hitchcock called Zadar's sunset the most beautiful in the world","Zadar's Church of Saint Donatus (9th century) is built almost entirely of Roman spolia — including stones with original Roman inscriptions visible inside the walls","The Maraschino liqueur (made from Marasca cherries) originated in Zadar in 1759 — Napoleon, the Habsburg court, and Queen Victoria were all enthusiasts","Zadar's Greeting to the Sun (2008) is a 22-metre solar disc embedded in the Riva that lights up at night to a programmed colour show","The Forum at the centre of Zadar's old town has been a public square since the 1st century BC — 2,000 years of continuous civic use"],
    vocab: [{"hr":"Zadranin","en":"person from Zadar","note":"Zadranin (m) / Zadranka (f) — Zadrani have a slight reserve compared to their Split neighbours, and a deep Italian-Dalmatian cultural inheritance"},{"hr":"Maraschino","en":"Zadar's signature liqueur","note":"Distilled from Marasca cherries since 1759. Still produced in Zadar — the bottle and label remain iconic"},{"hr":"Morske orgulje","en":"Sea Organ","note":"Bašić's wave-powered musical instrument on the Riva — one of Croatia's most famous post-2000 cultural creations"}],
    didYouKnow: "Alfred Hitchcock visited Zadar in 1964 and wrote: 'Zadar has the most beautiful sunset in the world, more beautiful than the one in Key West, in Florida, which is the most famous one.'",
