    intro: "Dugi Rat (literally 'Long Cape') is a coastal town between Omiš and Podstrana on the Makarska Riviera — a 7-kilometre strip of villages, beaches, and steep slopes where the Mosor mountain meets the sea. Industrial heritage and beach tourism sit side by side here.",
    history: "The Dugi Rat carbide and ferroalloy factory, opened in 1909, was for decades the largest industrial employer of the central Dalmatian coast — its harbour and rail spur shaped the town. Beach tourism developed alongside the industry from the 1960s. After Croatian independence the factory's slow decline left an open question about Dugi Rat's identity — coast or industrial town. Today it is firmly a beach town.",
    facts: ["The Dugi Rat factory (1909–2005) made calcium carbide and ferroalloys — once Yugoslavia's largest chemical works on the Adriatic coast","Dugi Rat's 7 km of coast contains 12 distinct beaches, mostly pebble","The Croatian Coast Guard (Hrvatska obalna straža) has a station in Dugi Rat","Mount Mosor above Dugi Rat reaches 1,339 metres — climbed by Split hikers in a 4-hour ascent","The town's Saint Stephen church (15th century) survived the WWII Allied bombing of the carbide factory"],
    vocab: [{"hr":"rat","en":"cape (in Dalmatian Croatian)","note":"Dugi Rat — Long Cape. 'Rat' as 'cape' is specifically Dalmatian; standard Croatian uses 'rt'"},{"hr":"Mosor","en":"the mountain behind Split-Dugi Rat","note":"Mosor — 1,339 m. The mountain range east of Split. Heavy snow in winter, hiking in summer"},{"hr":"tvornica","en":"factory","note":"The Dugi Rat tvornica — the chemical factory that defined the town's 20th century"}],
    didYouKnow: "Dugi Rat's carbide factory in 1944 was Allied-bombed because of its strategic value to Wehrmacht production — most of the bombs fell into the sea but two destroyed the worker housing.",
