    history: "Sutivan (whose name is a contraction of 'Sveti Ivan' — Saint John) was a Hvar-administered village in the late Middle Ages, then a Venetian one. Several Split and Hvar noble families built summer residences here — including the Definis (Definić), Marjanović-Definič, and the Tudisi families. The 16th-century Kaštel-Cerinić watchtower is the most prominent of these. The town became a quiet Yugoslav-era tourism destination from the 1960s.",
