    tagline: "Window of Gorski Kotar",
    intro: "Skrad is a forest village in Gorski Kotar — Croatia's mountainous northwestern region between Karlovac and Rijeka. The Vražji Prolaz (Devil's Passage) gorge and the Zeleni Vir (Green Whirlpool) waterfall just outside the village make Skrad one of Croatia's hidden natural treasures.",
    history: "Skrad was a forestry and railway village on the Zagreb–Rijeka line, opened in 1873. The Habsburg-era timber industry employed most of the local population. The Vražji Prolaz hiking trail through the dramatic gorge was opened in 1928 by Croatian alpinists. Tourism remained low-key through the Yugoslav and post-1991 periods. Today Skrad is a destination for mountain hikers and nature photographers.",
    facts: ["The Vražji Prolaz (Devil's Passage) gorge near Skrad is one of Croatia's most dramatic karst formations — 800 m of narrow rock canyon","The Zeleni Vir (Green Whirlpool) waterfall is a 70 m underground-river emergence — among Croatia's most distinctive water features","Skrad sits on the historic Zagreb–Rijeka railway — built 1873, one of Croatia's most scenic mountain lines","Gorski Kotar receives 2 to 3 metres of snow per winter — among the highest snowfall in Croatia","The village name 'Skrad' means 'hidden' or 'sheltered' in old Slavic — referring to its forested setting"],
