    intro: "Pribislavec is a small Međimurje municipality directly adjacent to Čakovec, known for the Festetics manor (Dvorac Festetics), a 19th-century country house built by the Hungarian Festetics noble family who held the Čakovec-area estates after the Zrinski dynasty was destroyed by the Habsburgs in 1671. The castle and its park dominate the village.",
    history: "After the execution of Petar Zrinski in 1671, the Habsburgs confiscated the Zrinski lands in Međimurje. The estates eventually came to the Festetics family, Hungarian nobles, who in the 19th century built a Romantic-historicist manor at Pribislavec. The Festetics estate was a large agricultural and forestry operation. After 1918 the estate passed to the new Yugoslav state, and the manor served various institutional functions. Pribislavec today is a small commuter community on Čakovec's eastern edge.",
    facts: ["Dvorac Festetics in Pribislavec was built in the 19th century by the Hungarian Festetics noble family","The Festetics acquired the Čakovec-area estates after the Zrinski lands were confiscated by the Habsburgs in 1671","Pribislavec sits directly adjacent to Čakovec in Međimurje County","The Festetics estate was historically one of the largest agricultural and forestry holdings in the region","Like all Međimurje, Pribislavec was part of Hungarian Zala County until 1918"],
