    intro: "Krašić is a municipality in Zagreb County in the hilly Žumberak area south of Jastrebarsko, best known as the birthplace in 1898 of Alojzije Stepinac — the wartime Archbishop of Zagreb, cardinal, and beatified Catholic martyr who was confined to Krašić by the Yugoslav communist authorities from 1951 until his death in 1960. The Stepinac birth house and parish are major pilgrimage sites.",
    history: "Krašić is an old hill-country parish in the Žumberak area, on the edge of the Greek Catholic (Eastern Rite) Žumberak diocese. Alojzije Stepinac was born here on 8 May 1898, became Archbishop of Zagreb in 1937, and led the Croatian Catholic Church through the Second World War, the Independent State of Croatia (NDH) period, and the early Yugoslav years. Tried and convicted by the Yugoslav regime in a controversial 1946 show trial, Stepinac was imprisoned at Lepoglava and then in 1951 transferred to house arrest in his birth village of Krašić, where he lived in the parish house until his death on 10 February 1960. Beatified by Pope John Paul II in 1998.",
    facts: ["Cardinal Alojzije Stepinac, wartime Archbishop of Zagreb, was born in Krašić on 8 May 1898","Stepinac was confined to the Krašić parish house by the Yugoslav authorities from December 1951 until his death on 10 February 1960","Stepinac was beatified by Pope John Paul II in Marija Bistrica on 3 October 1998","The Stepinac birth house and parish house in Krašić are pilgrimage sites managed as Stepinac memorial centres","Krašić lies in the Žumberak hill country south of Jastrebarsko, in Zagreb County"],
    vocab: [{"hr":"kardinal","en":"cardinal","note":"Krašić is the birthplace of kardinal Alojzije Stepinac — beatified Catholic martyr"},{"hr":"blaženi","en":"blessed (beatified)","note":"Blaženi Alojzije Stepinac — beatified by John Paul II in 1998 in Marija Bistrica"},{"hr":"kućni pritvor","en":"house arrest","note":"Stepinac lived under kućni pritvor in Krašić from 1951 to his death in 1960"}],
    didYouKnow: "Pope John Paul II personally beatified Cardinal Stepinac in Croatia at Marija Bistrica on 3 October 1998 — and visited Krašić itself, the village of Stepinac's birth and final confinement, on the same trip.",
