    intro: "Pomer is a small village on the western shore of Medulin Bay (Medulinski zaljev) at the southern tip of Istria, a few kilometres east of Pula. It is best known today for the ACI Marina Pomer, one of the oldest ACI marinas on the Adriatic, and for shallow, sheltered waters that make the bay a popular sailing and windsurfing area.",
    history: "Pomer was a small Venetian-era farming and fishing hamlet in the parish of Medulin; like neighbouring villages it had a mixed Croatian and Italian population under Venice (until 1797) and then Habsburg Austria. After Italy's brief interwar rule, the area passed to Yugoslavia in 1947, with most Italian-speakers leaving during the Istrian exodus. In 1983 ACI (Adriatic Croatia International Club) opened a marina at Pomer, one of the first in its network, anchoring the village's modern identity around nautical tourism rather than fishing.",
    facts: ["ACI Marina Pomer opened in 1983 and was among the founding marinas of the ACI chain — the largest Croatian nautical-tourism network","Pomer lies on the western shore of Medulinski zaljev, a shallow bay roughly 7 kilometres across and well-protected from the bora wind","The village is administratively part of Općina Medulin in Istria County","The shallow waters between Pomer and Medulin are popular with beginner windsurfers and kite-surfers","Pomer's parish church is dedicated to Saint Flor (Sveti Flor), an unusual dedication for southern Istria"],
