    tagline: "Bilingual Istrian-Italian village near Vodnjan",
    intro: "Galižana (Italian: Gallesano) is a village in southern Istria, between Pula and Vodnjan, with a strongly preserved Italian-speaking community and bilingual Croatian-Italian official status. It sits in agricultural countryside known for olive oil and red wine, and the centre retains a compact medieval-Venetian street plan around its parish church.",
    history: "Galižana appears in medieval documents from the 13th century; it was settled and partially resettled by Venetian authorities during the depopulation crises of the 16th and 17th centuries, bringing families from Friuli and the Venetian terra ferma. The Istrian-Venetian dialect (a Romance language related to Venetian) became, and remains, the everyday speech of much of the village. After 1945 the area entered Yugoslavia, but unlike many Istrian towns Galižana retained much of its Italian-speaking population. It is part of the bilingual administrative regime of Istria County.",
    facts: ["Galižana is one of the strongholds of the Istrian-Italian community in Croatia and is officially bilingual Croatian-Italian","The Istriot dialect of Galižana (locally called galižanjski) is a Romance language distinct from standard Italian and Venetian, now endangered","Galižana is administratively part of the City of Vodnjan-Dignano, itself bilingual","The village's parish church of Saints Justus and Cosmas dates in its current form to the 19th century, on older foundations","Galižana lies in some of Istria's most productive olive-growing land, with multiple award-winning olive oils"],
    vocab: [{"hr":"dvojezičan","en":"bilingual","note":"Galižana is officially dvojezična — Croatian and Italian — both languages appear on signs and in schools"},{"hr":"maslina","en":"olive","note":"Galižana sits in prime maslina country; Istrian olive oils from this area regularly win international awards"},{"hr":"narječje","en":"dialect","note":"The Istriot narječje of Galižana (galižanjski) is a small Romance language distinct from Italian and Venetian"}],
    didYouKnow: "The Istriot language spoken in Galižana is so distinct from standard Italian and modern Venetian that linguists classify it as a separate Romance branch — and Galižana is one of only six villages in the world where it is still actively spoken.",
