    tagline: "Eastern Istrian fishing village below Labin",
    intro: "Krnica is a small coastal village on the eastern side of the Istrian peninsula, roughly halfway between Pula and Labin, with a tiny fishing port (Krnička Luka) tucked into a narrow inlet below the village. The settlement is administratively part of Općina Marčana and retains a rural, low-density character with limited tourism development.",
    history: "Krnica has existed since at least the late medieval period under Venetian rule. Like other southern Istrian villages it was repopulated by Venice after plague-era depopulation. Under Habsburg Austria (1797–1918) it remained a small fishing and farming hamlet. Its small port served local boats and short-haul coastal traffic toward the Kvarner. After 1945 it joined Yugoslavia and then Croatia. Today the village is best known among Croatians for relatively unspoilt rocky beaches and the seafood konobas around Krnička Luka.",
    facts: ["Krnica is administratively part of Općina Marčana, in Istria County","Krnička Luka, the village's small fishing harbour, sits at the foot of the hill below the village proper","The village's parish church of Saint Roch sits at the centre of the old settlement","Krnica is one of the access points for kayakers exploring the eastern Istrian coastline toward Trget and Labin","The eastern Istrian coast at Krnica is notably less developed than the western Istrian coast, with predominantly rocky shoreline"],
    vocab: [{"hr":"lučica","en":"small harbour","note":"Krnička lučica — the small fishing harbour of Krnica, a narrow inlet below the village"},{"hr":"ribarska luka","en":"fishing port","note":"Krnica's ribarska luka still operates with small boats supplying the local konobas"},{"hr":"konoba","en":"traditional tavern","note":"The konobe of Krnička Luka are among the most-recommended seafood spots in eastern Istria"}],
    didYouKnow: "The Krnica coast faces the channel between Istria and the island of Cres, and on clear days you can see the Učka mountain to the north and the Cres lighthouse to the east — a 40-kilometre line of sight across open Adriatic.",
