    intro: "Sveti Petar u Šumi ('Saint Peter in the Forest') is a small village in central Istria, between Pazin and Žminj, named for its Pauline monastery and church of Saints Peter and Paul. The monastery, set among oak woodland, is one of the most important Baroque ecclesiastical complexes in Istria.",
    history: "The monastery at Sveti Petar u Šumi was founded in the 11th or 12th century as a Benedictine house, and was taken over by the Pauline Order (Pavlini) in 1459, who held it until the order's suppression by Emperor Joseph II in 1783. The current church and monastery buildings date principally to the late 17th and 18th centuries. Under Habsburg rule the monastery passed to the diocese; the Pauline Order returned to it in 1993, after Croatian independence. The village around the monastery has remained small but the church is a centre of regional pilgrimage.",
    facts: ["The Pauline Order (Pavlini) took over the monastery in 1459 and was suppressed there by Joseph II in 1783","The current Baroque church and monastery date principally to the 17th and 18th centuries","The Pavlini returned to the Sveti Petar monastery in 1993 after the order's restoration in Croatia","The wooden Baroque iconostasis-style altars inside the church are considered among the finest in Istria","The monastery's library historically held one of the largest collections of religious manuscripts in Istria"],
