    tagline: "Cliff village and birthplace of Eugen Kumičić",
    intro: "Brseč is a small clifftop village on the eastern slope of the Učka mountain, at the southern end of the Opatija Riviera, looking down a steep limestone drop to the Kvarner. The walled medieval core, perched on the cliff, was the birthplace in 1850 of the Croatian realist novelist Eugen Kumičić.",
    history: "Brseč is a Liburnian-origin hilltop settlement that became a small fortified Croatian and later Habsburg village, like other settlements along the Učka coast. Under Habsburg rule from the 15th century until 1918, it was administered as part of the Pazin/Rijeka holdings. The village's most famous son, Eugen Kumičić (1850–1904), grew up here and became one of the major figures of Croatian realist literature, with much of his work drawing on the Istrian coast he came from. After Italian and Yugoslav rule, Brseč is now part of Općina Mošćenička Draga in Primorje-Gorski Kotar County.",
    facts: ["Brseč is the birthplace of the Croatian novelist Eugen Kumičić (1850–1904), a leading figure of Croatian realism","The walled medieval village sits on a cliff above the Kvarner gulf at the southern end of the Opatija Riviera","Brseč's parish church of Saint George (Sveti Juraj) dates in its present form to the 18th century","The village is administratively part of Općina Mošćenička Draga in Primorje-Gorski Kotar County","The medieval walls and gate of Brseč are preserved as part of the town's protected historic core"],
    vocab: [{"hr":"književnik","en":"writer / man of letters","note":"Brseč's most famous književnik was Eugen Kumičić, a leading figure of Croatian realism, born here in 1850"},{"hr":"litica","en":"cliff","note":"Brseč sits on a litica above the Kvarner — one of the most dramatic clifftop villages on the eastern Adriatic"},{"hr":"realizam","en":"realism (literary)","note":"Eugen Kumičić of Brseč helped found Croatian književni realizam in the late 19th century"}],
    didYouKnow: "Eugen Kumičić of Brseč wrote the novel Začuđeni svatovi (1883), set among the Istrian coastal villages, and his birth-house in Brseč has been preserved as a small museum — one of the few literary-house museums in this part of Croatia.",
