    intro: "Selce is a small coastal town on the Vinodol coast immediately south of Crikvenica. Set on a gently descending slope toward the sea, with pebble beaches and a small harbour, Selce has been a quieter alternative to its larger neighbour Crikvenica since both developed as health resorts under late-Habsburg Austria.",
    history: "Selce belonged historically to the Vinodol domain of the Frankopan family, whose 1288 Vinodol Statute is one of the oldest surviving Slavic legal codes. Under the Frankopans and then the Habsburgs, Selce remained a small fishing and farming village. In the late 19th century, as Crikvenica boomed as an Austro-Hungarian seaside resort, Selce developed in parallel with smaller hotels and bathing establishments. Under Italian (briefly), Yugoslav and Croatian rule it continued as a tourist village, today part of the city of Crikvenica.",
    facts: ["Selce was historically part of the Frankopan Vinodol domain, governed under the 1288 Vinodol Statute — one of the oldest Slavic legal codes","The town is administratively part of the City of Crikvenica in Primorje-Gorski Kotar County","Selce developed as a small seaside resort in parallel with Crikvenica in the late 19th and early 20th centuries","The parish church of the Most Holy Trinity stands at the centre of the old village","Selce's pebble beaches stretch south toward Klenovica along the Vinodol coast"],
