    history: "Klenovica was part of the Frankopan Vinodol domain governed under the 1288 Vinodol Statute. Under the Frankopans, then the Habsburgs from the late 16th century, it remained a small fishing village. The bora-exposed position made the village's small harbour a critical refuge for boats caught out by sudden winds between Senj and Novi Vinodolski. Under Italian (briefly), Yugoslav and Croatian rule Klenovica has developed modestly as a small summer-tourism settlement, today part of the City of Novi Vinodolski.",
    facts: ["Klenovica is administratively part of the City of Novi Vinodolski in Primorje-Gorski Kotar County","The village faces the Velebit channel and is one of the most bora-exposed stretches of the eastern Adriatic coast","Klenovica was historically part of the Frankopan Vinodol governed under the 1288 Vinodol Statute","The bora wind at Klenovica can reach hurricane-force gusts during winter storms","The small harbour traditionally provided emergency refuge for boats caught between Senj and Novi Vinodolski"],
