    region: "Kvarner",
    icon: "🏛️",
    color: "#7c3aed",
    tagline: "Bronze-age cliff village on western Cres",
    intro: "Lubenice is a clifftop village on the western coast of the island of Cres, set on a limestone bluff 378 metres above the sea. The site has been continuously inhabited since the Bronze Age (around 4,000 years ago), making it one of the longest continuously inhabited settlements in Europe. Today fewer than two dozen permanent residents remain.",
    history: "Lubenice was first settled by Bronze Age peoples and has been continuously inhabited since — through Liburnian, Roman, medieval Croatian and Venetian periods. Under Venice from 1409 to 1797, it remained a fortified hilltop village. Like the rest of Cres it passed to Habsburg Austria, then Italy (1918–1947), then Yugoslavia. Twentieth-century depopulation reduced the village from several hundred residents to fewer than 30 today, but the stone settlement remains largely intact and protected as a cultural monument.",
    facts: ["Lubenice has been continuously inhabited since approximately the Bronze Age — about 4,000 years","The village sits on a limestone cliff 378 metres above the sea on Cres's western coast","Today fewer than 20 permanent residents remain in Lubenice","The stone village walls and houses are largely intact and protected under Croatian heritage law","The beach below Lubenice is one of the most photographed on the Adriatic — though it is reached only by a steep one-hour footpath"],
    vocab: [{"hr":"brončano doba","en":"Bronze Age","note":"Lubenice has been inhabited since the brončano doba — about 4,000 years — one of the longest continuous habitations in Europe"},{"hr":"litica","en":"cliff","note":"Lubenice sits on a 378-metre litica above the Adriatic — one of the most dramatic clifftop positions in Croatia"},{"hr":"selo duhova","en":"ghost village","note":"With under 20 permanent residents, Lubenice is sometimes called a selo duhova — though the village core is intact"}],
    didYouKnow: "The beach below Lubenice — visible as a perfect crescent of white pebbles 378 metres straight down from the village — is reachable only by a steep zig-zag footpath that takes roughly an hour each way, and it has appeared in multiple international lists of the most isolated and beautiful European beaches.",
