    intro: "Beli is a small village on the northeastern coast of the island of Cres, perched on a hill above the Kvarner. It is best known internationally as the home of the Beli Eco-Centre (Eko-centar Caput Insulae), which has been the centre of conservation efforts for the endangered Eurasian griffon vulture (bjeloglavi sup) since 1993.",
    history: "Beli is documented from antiquity — its position on the northeastern coast of Cres is identified with the Roman Caput Insulae ('head of the island'). The village was a small farming and seafaring community under medieval Croatian, then Venetian (1409–1797), then Habsburg rule. Under Italian (1918–1947), Yugoslav and Croatian rule it has continued as a small village. In 1993 the Beli Eco-Centre was established to monitor and protect the Eurasian griffon vulture population, which nests on the cliffs of northern Cres — one of the few remaining colonies in Europe.",
    facts: ["The Beli Eco-Centre (Eko-centar Caput Insulae), established in 1993, protects the endangered Eurasian griffon vulture","The griffon vulture (bjeloglavi sup) has a wingspan of up to 2.8 metres and nests on the cliffs of northern Cres","Beli is identified with the Roman 'Caput Insulae' — head of the island — at the northeastern tip of Cres","The village is administratively part of the City of Cres","Beli's hospital for injured vultures has rehabilitated and released hundreds of birds over three decades"],
