    intro: "Rogoznica is a small Dalmatian coastal town between Šibenik and Trogir, built on a former island connected to the mainland by a causeway. It is best known for Marina Frapa, one of the largest and most awarded nautical marinas on the Adriatic, and for the unusual saltwater lake Zmajevo Oko (Dragon's Eye).",
    history: "Rogoznica was first mentioned in 1390 as Rogosnica, a fishing settlement under the Šibenik commune during Venetian and later Habsburg rule. For centuries it was a poor village of fishermen and olive growers, its small island connected to the mainland only by a wooden bridge until the 20th century. The opening of Marina Frapa in 1995 transformed Rogoznica into a major nautical-tourism centre, while the village core around the parish church of the Assumption preserves the older Dalmatian fabric.",
    facts: ["Marina Frapa, opened in 1995 in the Soline bay, has won the ADAC and TOMAS awards for best Croatian marina multiple times","Zmajevo Oko is a karst saltwater lake about 15 metres deep, separated from the sea only by a thin limestone wall","Rogoznica was originally an island, joined to the mainland by a causeway built in the 18th century","The parish church of the Assumption of Mary sits on the highest point of the old island core","The protected Cape Ploča (Punta Planka) south of Rogoznica is the boundary between northern and central Dalmatian waters in classical Adriatic geography"],
