    intro: "Žirje is the most distant inhabited island of the Šibenik archipelago, lying about 22 kilometres from Šibenik in the open Adriatic. With under 100 permanent residents in two villages — Muna and Brbinjšćak — and connected by a roughly two-hour ferry from Šibenik, Žirje is one of the least populated yet historically most strategic Croatian islands.",
    history: "Žirje has been inhabited since prehistoric times; Roman and early Christian remains have been found at Gradina and Velika Gospa. In the early Byzantine period the island held two fortresses, Gradina and Gustijerna, controlling the maritime approach to the mainland against Slavic incursions in the 6th century. Under the Šibenik commune through the Venetian and Habsburg eras, Žirje was farmed for vineyards, olives, and figs. In World War II it was an Allied submarine base; today it is best known for diving, fishing, and the Stupica beaches.",
    facts: ["Žirje is the most remote inhabited island of the Šibenik archipelago, roughly 22 km from Šibenik harbour","Two early-Byzantine fortresses — Gradina and Gustijerna — survive on the island from the 6th century","The two settlements Muna and Brbinjšćak together hold under 100 year-round residents","Velika and Mala Stupica on the south coast are among the most-photographed coves in the Šibenik archipelago","The island's name derives from žir — acorn — referring to dense oak woods used for pig-fattening in earlier centuries"],
