    tagline: "Šibenik's Sponge-Diving Gateway to Krapanj",
    intro: "Brodarica is a coastal settlement south of Šibenik, directly across a narrow channel from the island of Krapanj. Historically the mainland base for Krapanj's famous sponge divers, Brodarica is now a sprawling residential and tourist suburb of Šibenik, with a small port from which a five-minute boat connects to Krapanj.",
    history: "Brodarica was founded as a mainland settlement of Krapanj islanders who needed pastureland and freshwater wells unavailable on their tiny island. Through the Venetian and Habsburg periods the two communities were a single economic unit, with Brodarica supplying agricultural produce and Krapanj specializing in sponge-diving. The name comes from brod (boat or ship), reflecting the constant ferrying between mainland and island. In the second half of the 20th century Brodarica grew rapidly as a Šibenik suburb, absorbing summer-house tourism along the channel.",
    facts: ["Brodarica's name comes from brod (boat) — referring to ferrying between mainland and Krapanj island","The channel between Brodarica and Krapanj is barely 300 metres wide, the shortest island crossing in Dalmatia","Most Brodarica families historically also owned property and graves on Krapanj","The parish church of Saint Christopher (Sveti Krševan) faces the Krapanj channel","Brodarica is now effectively a southern suburb of Šibenik along the D8 coastal road"],
    vocab: [{"hr":"brod","en":"boat / ship","note":"Root of Brodarica's name — the place of boats ferrying to Krapanj across the channel"},{"hr":"brodar","en":"boatman / ferryman","note":"The brodari of Brodarica historically rowed islanders to and from Krapanj all day"},{"hr":"kanal","en":"channel, strait","note":"Krapanjski kanal — barely 300 m wide, the shortest island ferry crossing in Croatia"}],
    didYouKnow: "The Brodarica–Krapanj ferry is among the shortest scheduled boat lines in the world: the crossing takes less than five minutes, and during the busiest summer months boats run almost continuously through the day.",
