    intro: "Klek is a small Croatian coastal village just west of the Bosnia-Herzegovina border at Neum, in Dubrovnik-Neretva County. Sitting on a long shallow sandy bay, Klek is the last Croatian settlement before the brief Bosnian access to the sea splits Croatia into two parts. With about 200 permanent residents, Klek functions today as a quiet family beach destination.",
    history: "Klek takes its name from the karst hill above it called Klek, after the Croatian word for an ancient juniper. The village developed as a small fishing and farming settlement under the Republic of Ragusa (Dubrovnik) and later the Habsburgs. Its strategic importance increased only in the modern era because of its position adjacent to the Neum corridor — the small stretch of coast given to the Ottoman Empire in 1699 by the Republic of Ragusa as a buffer against Venetian expansion, and inherited by Bosnia and Herzegovina in modern times. Klek is now a quiet beach village with shallow warm water suited to families.",
    facts: ["Klek is the last Croatian coastal village west of the Neum corridor in Bosnia-Herzegovina","The Neum corridor was ceded by the Republic of Ragusa to the Ottoman Empire in 1699","Klek sits in Dubrovnik-Neretva County and belongs to the Slivno municipality","Its long shallow sandy bay is unusual on the otherwise rocky Dalmatian coast","The village name derives from the Croatian word for an old juniper tree (klek)"],
