    tagline: "Dubrovnik's Southern Frontier Region",
    intro: "Konavle is the southernmost region of Croatia, the long karst valley running from the Dubrovnik suburbs south-east to the Montenegrin border. Rather than a single settlement, Konavle is a historic region of villages, vineyards, and pastures, with its own distinctive folk costume, dialect, and identity. The administrative seat is Cavtat; other villages include Pridvorje, Gruda, Čilipi, and Molunat.",
    history: "Konavle takes its name from the Latin canalis, referring to a Roman-era canal that once ran through the valley. The region was purchased outright by the Republic of Ragusa in two stages — 1419 from the Bosnian king Stjepan Ostojić and 1426 from the Pavlović family — for 12,000 ducats and an annual tribute. Konavle then became Ragusa's most important agricultural hinterland for four centuries. The region's villages preserve some of the most distinctive Croatian folk costumes, embroidery, and music. In the 1991 Homeland War much of Konavle was occupied by Yugoslav and Serbian-Montenegrin forces and partially burned; it was liberated by autumn 1992.",
    facts: ["Konavle was bought outright by the Republic of Ragusa in two stages in 1419 and 1426","The total purchase price was approximately 12,000 ducats plus an annual tribute","Konavle takes its name from the Latin canalis — the Roman-era valley canal","The Konavle folk costume with its distinctive red-and-black embroidery is among the most recognized in Croatia","Much of Konavle was occupied and burned during the 1991 Homeland War and liberated in 1992"],
